{
    "analysis": "From the previous Executor output we confirmed metric.csv, trace.csv and log.csv are populated (each with 25 points per group) and error_logs.csv is empty. There are 69 distinct cmdb_id values in the data. The telemetry contains many ts-* services and many KPI groups. To follow the required workflow we must now focus only on the allowed candidate components (ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service) and compute global thresholds for each component-KPI time series using the full available series (no time filtering yet). These thresholds will be used to detect anomalies within the incident window (2024-01-25 10:31:10 to 2024-01-25 11:01:10 UTC).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the full metric.csv, trace.csv, and log.csv (do not filter by incident time yet), filter rows where cmdb_id is one of: ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service. For each remaining file produce a compact summary grouped by (cmdb_id, KPI_name) where KPI_name is kpi_name for metric.csv, trace_name for trace.csv, and log_name for log.csv. For each group compute: count, mean(value), p50, p90, p95, p5, min, and max. Return results as three separate tables (metric / trace / log), each limited to at most 100 rows, sorted by cmdb_id then kpi_name. Also return a short listing of which of the five candidate cmdb_ids exist in each file (present/absent). Keep outputs compact."
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous steps: We preprocessed metrics/traces/logs and computed global thresholds per (component-KPI) using full series. Metric analysis (with p90 loosened) found multiple short faults (mostly 3-point runs) across candidate services. The earliest significant cluster of metric anomalies occurred at ~2024-01-25T10:34:00Z in ts-order-service (latency-50, mem, socket, cpu). Later, brief spikes appeared in ts-train-service (~10:47:00Z) and ts-auth/ts-route (~10:56:00Z). Trace-level analysis so far only flagged many error_rate series, but those were artifacts (global p90/p95 == 0 and all zeros in-window). To localize the root cause we must use traces for duration metrics to find which service is actually experiencing latency or elevated durations in traces and to determine call chains: the root cause service should be the most downstream faulty service in traces. Given metric timing, ts-order-service at ~10:34 is the primary candidate to inspect via traces (it had multiple resource + latency anomalies earliest). Next we should inspect trace duration metrics (duration_mean, duration_p95, and row_count) for traces involving ts-order-service (both traces emitted by ts-order-service and traces from other services calling ts-order-service) to see whether traces show duration spikes in the same window and whether ts-order-service is downstream faulty in end-to-end traces.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Analyze trace.csv focusing on traces that mention the order service during the full series and in the incident window: select rows where (cmdb_id == 'ts-order-service') OR (trace_name contains 'to_ts-order-service') OR (trace_name contains 'from_ts-order-service'). From the full series compute global p95 and p90 for each (cmdb_id, trace_name). Then filter trace rows to the incident window 2024-01-25T10:31:10Z — 2024-01-25T11:01:10Z. For each group (cmdb_id, trace_name) and for trace_name in {contains 'duration_mean', 'duration_p95', 'row_count'} compute: global_p95, global_p90, anomaly_count_p95 (count of window points >= global_p95), anomaly_count_p90 (count >= global_p90), earliest_anomaly_ts_p90 (ISO UTC or null), mean_in_window, max_in_window. Return up to top 20 rows where anomaly_count_p90 > 0, sorted by anomaly_count_p90 desc then anomaly_count_p95 desc. Keep output compact and include source cmdb_id, trace_name, global_p95, global_p90, anomaly_count_p95, anomaly_count_p90, earliest_anomaly_ts_p90, mean_in_window, max_in_window."
}

{
    "analysis": "The trace-focused analysis showed that traces involving ts-order-service had the earliest and most consistent anomalies in the incident window (~2024-01-25T10:34:00Z): elevated row_count and increased durations (duration_mean / duration_p95). Earlier metric scans also showed ts-order-service had concurrent metric spikes around that time (latency-50, mem, socket, cpu), with several groups showing 3 consecutive points >= global p90. Among those, the cpu metric for ts-order-service had a markedly larger absolute deviation (max_in_window ~30.5 vs global p95 ~12.1), suggesting a strong CPU spike, while mem/socket deviations were smaller in relative terms. Trace anomalies indicate the order service is part of the affected call chains and appears to be the earliest downstream faulty service in traces. Error/error_rate series and error_logs were essentially zero during the window, so the issue appears to be resource-induced latency rather than application errors.\nGiven these findings, the next step is to confirm and quantify ts-order-service resource pressure during the incident: validate CPU, memory, socket, and latency metrics specifically for ts-order-service in the incident window (global thresholds from full series), compute severity ratios (value / p95), anomaly counts (>=p90 and >=p95), earliest anomaly timestamps, longest consecutive runs >= p90, and include log.row_count in-window for correlation. This will confirm which resource (CPU/memory/socket/latency) is the most likely root cause.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For ts-order-service only, analyze metric.csv for these kpi_name values: cpu, mem, socket, latency-50, latency-90. Using the full available series compute global_p95, global_p90, global_p5 for each KPI (do NOT filter by the incident window when computing thresholds). Then filter metric rows to the incident window 2024-01-25T10:31:10Z — 2024-01-25T11:01:10Z and for each KPI compute: anomaly_count_p95 (count of window points >= global_p95), anomaly_count_p90 (count >= global_p90), earliest_anomaly_ts_p90 (ISO UTC or null), max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, longest_consecutive_run_p90 (longest consecutive window points >= global_p90), and max_severity_ratio = max(value/global_p95) among window points (if global_p95==0, set ratio to null). Also return ts-order-service log.row_count stats in the window: count_of_points_in_window, mean_row_count_in_window, max_row_count_in_window, earliest_timestamp_in_window. Return a compact table with one row per KPI plus the log.row_count row, limit output to these rows only." }

